  "primaryContentSections": [
    {
      "kind": "content",
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "overview",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Overview",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "If you don't plan to use gesture recognizers with a custom view, you can handle touch events directly from the view itself. Because views are responders, they can handle Multi-Touch events and many other types of events. When UIKit determines that a touch event occurred in a view, it calls the view’s "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/uikit/uiresponder/1621142-touchesbegan"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/uikit/uiresponder/1621107-touchesmoved"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ", or "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/uikit/uiresponder/1621084-touchesended"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " method. You can override these methods in your custom views and use them to provide a response to touch events."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "The methods you override in your views (or in any responder) to handle touches correspond to different phases of the touch event–handling process. For example, "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "link-media-3004382"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " illustrates the different phases of a touch event. When a finger (or Apple Pencil) touches the screen, UIKit creates a "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/uikit/uitouch"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " object, sets the touch location to the appropriate point, and sets its "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/uikit/uitouch/1618113-phase"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property to "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/uikit/uitouchphase/uitouchphasebegan"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ". When the same finger moves around the screen, UIKit updates the touch location and changes the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/uikit/uitouch/1618113-phase"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property of the touch object to "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/uikit/uitouchphase/uitouchphasemoved"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ". When the user lifts the finger from the screen, UIKit changes the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/uikit/uitouch/1618113-phase"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property to "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/uikit/uitouchphase/uitouchphaseended"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " and the touch sequence ends."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "image",
              "identifier": "media-3004382",
              "metadata": {
                "anchor": "3004382",
                "title": "Figure 1",
                "abstract": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "The phases of a touch event"
                  }
                ]
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Similarly, the system may cancel an ongoing touch sequence at any time; for example, when an incoming phone call interrupts the app. When it does, UIKit notifies your view by calling the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/uikit/uiresponder/1621116-touchescancelled"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " method. You use that method to perform any needed cleanup of your view’s data structures."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "UIKit creates a new "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/uikit/uitouch"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " object for each new finger that touches the screen. The touches themselves are delivered with the current "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/uikit/uievent"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " object. UIKit distinguishes between touches originating from a finger and from Apple Pencil, and you can treat each of them differently."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "aside",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "inlineContent": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "In its default configuration, a view receives only the first "
                },
                {
                  "type": "reference",
                  "isActive": true,
                  "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/uikit/uitouch"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": " object associated with an event, even if more than one finger is touching the view. To receive the additional touches, you must set the view’s "
                },
                {
                  "type": "reference",
                  "isActive": true,
                  "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/uikit/uiview/1622519-multipletouchenabled"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": " property to true. You can also configure this property in Interface Builder using the Attributes inspector."
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "style": "important"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
